  "prompt": "What are the rules for Yahoo's fantasy hockey?",
  "response": "Yahoo Fantasy Hockey rules are pretty standard for fantasy hockey, but here's a breakdown of the key aspects you'll need to understand:\n\n**1. League Types & Settings:**\n\n*   **Public Leagues:** Open to anyone. You can join a random league or search for a specific type. Generally Standard scoring.\n*   **Private Leagues:** Invite-only. Commissioners customize all settings.\n*   **Standard Leagues (Default Settings):** Usually use head-to-head format, basic scoring categories, and a set roster.\n*   **Custom Leagues:** Commissioners have control over everything (roster sizes, scoring, playoffs, keeper settings, etc.).\n\n**2. Roster Structure (Very Common):**\n\n*   **Typical Positions:** C (Center), LW (Left Wing), RW (Right Wing), D (Defenseman), G (Goalie), BN (Bench), IR (Injured Reserve), IR+ (Injured Reserve+ - may include covid, LTIR)\n*   **Number of Players:** Usually around 18-22 total players depending on league setup.  The bench spots are important to fill.\n*   **Daily/Weekly Lineups:** You'll need to set your active roster (players in starting positions) daily or weekly, depending on the league settings.  Pay attention to the schedule.\n\n**3. Scoring:**\n\n*   **Head-to-Head (Most Common):** Each week, your team is matched up against another team in the league. The team with the higher total in most stat categories wins the matchup for that week.\n*   **Points:**  Teams accumulate points based on the stats their players accrue. The team with the most total points at the end of the season wins.\n*   **Rotisserie (Roto):** Teams are ranked in each stat category. Points are awarded based on where you rank in each category. (Ex: 1st gets most points, last gets the least)\n*   **Common Stat Categories for Skaters:**\n    *   Goals (G)\n    *   Assists (A)\n    *   Points (P) - Goals + Assists\n    *   Plus/Minus (+/-)\n    *   Power Play Points (PPP)\n    *   Shots on Goal (SOG)\n    *   Hits (HIT)\n    *   Blocked Shots (BLK)\n    *   Penalty Minutes (PIM)\n*   **Common Stat Categories for Goalies:**\n    *   Wins (W)\n    *   Goals Against Average (GAA)\n    *   Save Percentage (SV%)\n    *   Shutouts (SHO)\n    *   Saves (SV)\n\n**4. Draft:**\n\n*   **Live Draft:** All managers are online at the same time, picking players in a pre-determined order.\n*   **Auto-Pick:** The system automatically drafts players for you based on pre-set rankings. Risky, but can work in a pinch.\n*   **Snake Draft:** The most common. The draft order reverses each round (1-2-3-4... / ...4-3-2-1).\n*   **Auction Draft:** Managers bid on players using a budget.\n*   **Offline Draft:** Manually drafted, and the commisioner enters the results into Yahoo.\n\n**5. Waivers & Free Agency:**\n\n*   **Waivers:** When a player is dropped, they are placed on waivers.  Teams can claim them, with priority based on waiver settings.  (e.g., reverse standings). It takes a day or two for waiver claims to process.\n*   **Free Agency:** Players who are not owned and have cleared waivers are free to be added to your roster.\n*   **Waiver Priority:** Determines the order in which teams get to claim players on waivers.  Common methods:\n    *   Reverse Order of Standings (Worst team gets first priority)\n    *   Continuous Rolling List (Once you claim a player, you go to the bottom of the list)\n\n**6. Trades:**\n\n*   You can propose trades to other managers in your league.\n*   Trades may be subject to a league vote or a commissioner veto.\n*   There's usually a trade deadline during the season.\n\n**7. Playoffs:**\n\n*   The top teams in the league (usually 4, 6, or 8 depending on the league size) qualify for the playoffs.\n*   Playoffs are head-to-head matchups that typically last 1-2 weeks per round.\n*   The winner of the final playoff round is the league champion.\n\n**8. Commissioner Powers (Private Leagues):**\n\n*   The commissioner has extensive powers to manage the league, including:\n    *   Setting up the league rules.\n    *   Overruling trades.\n    *   Adjusting rosters in exceptional circumstances.\n    *   Resolving disputes.\n\n**Important Considerations & Tips:**\n\n*   **League Settings are King:** The most important thing is to understand *your specific league's settings.*  Don't assume anything.  Review all the rules and categories *before* the draft.\n*   **Pay Attention to Player News:** Stay updated on injuries, line changes, and call-ups. This is crucial for making informed roster decisions.  Yahoo's fantasy platform integrates player news.\n*   **Stream Players:** If you are in a league that counts daily transactions, try to swap out players who have already played for one that is playing tonight.\n*   **Scarcity is Key:** Learn to recognize when a position or stat category is in high demand. Draft accordingly. For example, good goalies are often drafted early.\n*   **Veto Judiciously:** In leagues with vetoes, trades should only be vetoed if there's clear collusion (two teams working together unfairly) or a gross imbalance that ruins the league.\n*   **Be Active:**  The more active you are in managing your roster, the better your chances of success.\n\n**Where to Find Specific Rules:**\n\n*   **League Homepage:** On your Yahoo Fantasy Hockey league homepage, there's usually a link to \"League Settings\" or \"League Rules.\" This is where you'll find the definitive information.\n*   **Help Section:** Yahoo Fantasy Sports has a help section with detailed information on all aspects of the game.\n\nGood luck with your fantasy hockey season!\n",
